Stop Doing These Things If You Want Results ⬇️

🥩 Not hitting your Protein goals: Protein is the building block of our muscles. To build muscle, you should aim to get about 0.7-1 grams of protein per pound of body weight daily. If you aren’t hitting this goal, you’re not giving your muscles the tools they need to repair and grow. 

🏃‍♀️ Overdoing cardio: Cardio is great for heart health and burning calories (calories used to build muscle too), but too much can lead to muscle loss if it’s not balanced with strength training. Try walking on an incline for 20-30 min post workout instead. 

💤Skipping rest days: Your body needs time to repair and recover. This is where your muscles GROW. If you’re not resting properly you can stall your growth and even cause injury. Next time you’re thinking about skipping your “rest days” remember that your body is hard at work building!

🔄 Doing different workouts: Consistency is key. Jumping from one workout routine to another can confuse your muscles and stall your progress. While it’s good to mix things up occasionally, having a solid routine that you stick to is crucial. This way your muscles can grow and progress! 

⏳ Looking for quick fixes: True progress takes time. There’s no way around it. Avoid fad diets, “magic” supplements, or any program that promises results overnight. Sustainable results come from consistent effort, proper nutrition, and most of all, patience.

It’s the commitment that makes all the difference 🩵

Eat real food👇🏼

I’ve said it once, I’ll say it again. Dieting does not work long term 🙅🏻‍♀️ You may lose a few lbs for an event or vacation, but chances are those lbs are coming right back to you 🫠

How do we prevent the seesaw that is “diet culture”? We stop dieting. Take a really good look at your habits and the foods you consume on a ✨daily✨ basis. 

How often are you having real whole foods rather than pre packaged options? How often are you eating processed foods? 🥬🥕🍅

Keep it simple and look for ways to make easy meals with whole ingredients (I can help with that 🫶🏻). Instead of grabbing a sugary packaged yogurt, grab some plain Greek yogurt and add some honey 🍯 to it. 

A healthier lifestyle is a bunch of small changes stacked up to give you long lasting results. Before you can change your life, you have to change what you accept as your norm. That means what you eat, how often you move, and how well you take care of yourself. 

Leave any questions you have about food, nutrition or fitness in the comments 🩵

Stay fit friends! ✨

Discipline >  Motivation 

I’ve gotten a lot of questions as to how I stay motivated to go to the gym. The real answer is I’m not. Most days, I’d happily curl up with Netflix if I listened to my mood. 🛋️🍿

A little while ago I stopped letting my mood dictate my actions. I trained myself to act out of discipline, making my workouts and health routines non-negotiable. Just like brushing my teeth, I don’t even think about it. 

Next time you’re looking for motivation to go to the gym, don’t. You likely won’t find it. Just lace up your shoes, blast your music and MOVE. 

Motivation is fleeting, it’s inconsistent, but discipline will always be there. Create habits so strong that you don’t give your brain the time to make excuses 🧠

So, to anyone curious about how I stay so ‘motivated’? It’s not motivation, friends. It’s rock-solid discipline. Build that, and you’ll be unstoppable🔥

Working out during your ✨luteal phase🌙

If you see me yawning through my workout mind your business 🙃 I’m doing my best 

Every so often I get to the gym and realize the weights aren’t moving like they used to, my muscles hurt a little bit more, and my energy is low. This is likely because I’m in my ✨luteal phase 🌙

What is the luteal phase: Luteal phase is the time before the start of your new cycle (~1-2 weeks before). Around the time you’ll feel low energy, you likely won’t be able to lift as heavy, and your whole workout may feel like an uphill battle. 

During this time I try to listen to my body and adjust my workout intensity or focus more on mobility. Some months I can breeze through the phase and other months it hits me like a truck. 

It can feel like you’re taking 2 steps forward and 1 step back when it comes to progress, but be patient and remember that it’s totally normal for your energy to ebb and flow.

Can’t wish your goals to come true 🙃

This is the part where I get brutally honest and tell people that there is no magic cure. You have to show up. You have to make time (whatever that looks like for you) and most of all you have to be consistent. 

That’s why I emphasize finding a workout or way to move your body that works for you and fits into your life. Make your health and fitness a non-negotiable and the progress and change will come. 

It’s much easier said than done, but at the end of the day it’s your choice. You choose the life you want. So choose wisely 🫶🏻

Some moments that don’t even come close to capturing this whole trip 🤍
 
From Lebanon, to Greece to Armenia it was a wild ride ✈️🌎

Work hard play hard 🫶🏻

Instead of putting pressure on myself to eat a certain way, keep up with my habits, or hit a certain number of steps, I let go and enjoyed every single bit of my trip! 

I have a sweet tooth so I definitely indulged in the pastries, ice creams and something I never have… soda. The most important part what was fueling my body so I can do all the activities and not punishing myself for any of it when I got back.

There can be a lot of anxiety around food and gym schedules, but I promise you if you have been putting in the work, a few weeks or even a few months off aren’t going to make all of that disappear. 

So take the extra day off, enjoy the ice cream and remember this fitness thing is a LIFE long journey. There’s no rush to get to where you’re going. 

Love, your friendly neighborhood gym girl 🫶🏻🩷

Vacation might be over, but the post-trip reset is in full swing! 🌴➡️🏋️‍♀️ 

Here’s how I’m getting back on track after indulging on vacation:

1️⃣ Hydration Hydration Hydration! Loaded up on water to flush out the vacation bloat and rehydrate my body.

2️⃣ Back to Basics: Returned to my go-to, nutrient-dense meals. Nothing like home-cooked goodness to reset.

3️⃣ Moved My Body: Started with some light exercises and stretching before diving back into my regular routine.

4️⃣ Sleep Schedule: Early to bed, early to rise. Got my sleep cycle back on track.

5️⃣ Mindful Moments: Took time each day to meditate and reflect. Grateful for the vacay but also for the routine.

6️⃣ Set Mini Goals: Planned out my workouts and meals for the week. Having a roadmap makes it easier!

It’s totally okay to indulge and enjoy on vacation - that’s what they’re for! But there’s no feeling quite like getting back into your groove. How do you reset post-vacation? Drop your tips below! ✈️🔄🥗

Everything you need to know about ✨Body Recomposition✨

There is so much fluff out there about the “secret sauce”, “morning concoction”, or workout that will give you the body you’re after. 

There’s no way around the formula to get there. Simply put, the key to looking toned is building muscle because they burn calories for you at rest! It’s an investment 🤌🏼

Here’s how to lose fat and gain muscle⬇️

1. Workouts: you need be lifting weights 3-5 x a week and progressively overloading. This can mean slowing down your reps, adding weight, or adding volume (more reps). Either way you need to be increasing the intensity so your muscles can adapt to the new demands. 

2. Protein: you need to fuel your muscles with lots of protein. You should have ~1g per lb of body weight. For example if I weigh 130lbs, I should be having 130g of protein. If you are eating in a caloric deficit, you should be having more.

3. Supplements: stay on top of your supplements like amino complex’s (BCAAs) and creatine to help support your muscle building. 

4. Caloric maintenance: ✨surprise✨you don’t have to be in a deficit to lose fat. If you are at maintenance calories, lifting heavy and hitting your protein (while it will take longer) you are more likely to maintain your muscle and lose fat in the process. Being in a caloric deficit also takes nutrients from your muscles so you’ll inevitably lose both fat and muscle. 

5. Walking: this might be a secret sauce but the science says when you are in a low intensity state like walking, your body is able to use fats for energy (they take longer to use so when you need a lot of energy and fast for things like a squat, your body won’t burn fat). Any kind of low intensity movement throughout your day will do wonders for helping you maintain your muscle and burn through fat.

Start with these steps and I promise you’ll be well on your way to achieving your goals!

Full outfit is @oneractive 

I love the comfort zone as much as anyone, but if you are struggling to make progress you need to be honest with yourself. 

Are you really pushing your limits? Or are you secretly staying within the 10 rep zone and ending your set when it starts to burn? 🔥 

At a certain point I was struggling to make progress and couldn’t figure out why. Then I got honest with myself and realized I could push more. 

Every time I thought, “I’ve definitely been pushing to my limits”… I tested it anyway. WITHOUT FAIL, I have always had at least a little more to give. 

Don’t be afraid of the discomfort. Your sets don’t end when it starts to burn. 

Embrace the discomfort and watch yourself grow. In those moments when you give more where you thought you had nothing left… that’s where the magic happens. That’s where you see progress. 

So add that weight ✨ even if you only do it once or twice, that’s your new limit. 

When was the last time you really pushed yourself?

Lentil soup is seriously so underrated ⭐️ it’s oniony, hearty and is also really good for you! 

If you didn’t know, lentils are high in B vitamins, iron, magnesium, zinc and protein 👌🏼

What you need to make it:
+ Whole onion chopped 
+ 4 large carrots (shredded)
+ Red lentil 2 cups (wash)
+ Chicken bouillon 2 tbsp
+ Medium grain rice 3/4 cup 

✨ Fill water until 3/4 of the full pot. Add everything to the pot. Bring to a rolling boil then simmer on low heat and stir for 45 min.

✨Once done cooking, chop an additional whole onion sautéed in olive oil (enough to coat the bottom of the pan) until lightly caramelized and put with oil into the pot.

Slow and steady wins the race 🐌

You want to see results? Stop chasing your ego by stacking as many plates as possible and rushing through your set. Drop the weight and slow it way down. 

When you slow down your reps you increase the time under tension forcing your muscles to work throughout the entire movement. 

Which means more muscle recruitment/growth ✨🎧

This was one of the methods I used to break a plateau. I couldn’t figure out why I was busting my butt in the gym and not seeing any muscle growth. I still do this, because it helps me feel the tension throughout the entire movement 🍑

Here’s how I apply this method: 
+ count 4 seconds on the way down 
+ explode into full extension 
+ hold at the top for 1-2 seconds 
+ rise and 🔁

The elusive abs 💭  and no crunches won’t give you abs

The first thing we need to understand about ✨visible✨ abs is that the only way to “have them”, is to be at a certain body fat percentage. 

If you cannot see your abs, you likely have them, just need to eat in a slight caloric deficit until you do.

Here’s how to actually get them 

1. Walking: truly a secret gem when it comes to dropping fat without compromising muscle loss. Your body uses fat for energy during low-moderate intensity exercise. Trust me on this one. 

2. EAT: while you should be at a certain body fat percentage to see them, in order to get there you need to consistently be in a caloric deficit. A great way to do this is by eating filling healthy meals so you avoid snacking or caving to unhealthy foods. 

3. Compound movements: squats, deadlifts, hip thrusts are all exercises that can be used to challenge your core. While isolating the ab muscles is great, you should also be working them during your lifts for best results 🤌🏼

4. Genetics 🧬 - at the end of the day, some people carry more fat around their mid section meaning they will need to reach a lower body fat percentage to see them (since you cannot spot reduce fat).

RDL Cues to Grow Your Glutes 🍑

Romanian Deadlifts are a master movement for strengthening and growing your glutes IF you’re doing them properly. 

Here’s are some do’s and dont’s for a glute biased RDL ⬇️

DO:
✅ place feet hip width apart
✅ maintain a neutral spine 
✅ hinge your hips to about mid shin 
✅ pretend like you’re closing a door behind you with your butt 
✅ soft bend your knees to feel your glutes 
✅ pull up with your hamstrings and glutes
✅ feel a stretch in your hamstrings and glutes 

DON’T: 
❌ round your back or lower with your torso (ouch) 
❌ lower too far down (mid shin is fine)
❌ pretend like you’re picking something up from the floor 
❌ lock out your knees at the top
❌ push your hips forward at the top 
❌ lift your head up to see yourself in the mirror (neck should be in line with your spine) 
❌ feel a lot of tension in your low back 

Save this one to make sure you’re doing them correctly! 

Happy lifting 🤍

Reveal your hard work in the kitchen 🔪⏲️

Without proper nutrition, your results will be minimal. Simple as that 🤷🏻‍♀️ 

Here are some steps to make sure you’re on track to hit your goals in 2024: 

1. Find out what your maintainence calories are ⚖️ then eat 100-300 calories above or below that (depending on your goals) 

2. Stick to whole foods 🍎 Do away with pre packaged food so you can control what you are consuming. Eat balanced filling meals made with good ingredients to fight off cravings.

3. Keep a food journal 📔 I don’t like tracking macros daily, but a journal entry about every quarter to keep you conscious of what you’re eating is always a good way to stay on track. 

4. Enjoy foods you love, but make them yourself 🔪. At the end of the day you need to make a lifestyle change if you are used to eating out a lot. Quick easy recipes are all over the internet (and my page 🫶🏻). Find them, prep them, eat them. 

I have lots of recipes and workouts on my page 🤍 save this to remind you to stay on top of your nutrition 🌱

Glute biased step up cues you need to know 💭

It took me a while to get this one down so let me help you out, friend 🙃

+ First you’ll need to choose the right height. Go too high and you won’t be able to control it all the way down, go too low and you won’t get that stretch in your glute. A nice average height is a bench 👍🏼

+ Start with low weight 🏋️‍♀️ You can likely do more weight if you push through with your quads but we want slow, controlled and glute focused. 

+ To make it glute focused I want you to not just step down but step back onto the floor 🍑 Hinge at your hips and lean forward to feel the stretch in your glute while you do it. 

+ Don’t push off with your back foot 💨 Your front foot should be bearing all the weight both on the way down and way up. 

Note: if you have a knee injury start with no weight and slowly work your way up. It’s not impossible to do it comfortably, but it will take time 

Hope this helps 🫶🏻
